n%20or%20out%20of%20corporate%20life%20in%20nontraditional%20ways.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Faside%3E%5Cn%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22ff2e2970-c89c-4252-98da-a4e6927d2307%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EBecoming%20an%20astronaut%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EI%20fell%20in%20love%20with%20space%20in%20high%20school.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EI%20majored%20in%20physics%20at%20college%2C%20and%20got%20a%20graduate%20degree%20in%20engineering.%20I%20dreamed%20of%20working%20with%20NASA%20building%20spaceships.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAfter%20completing%20a%20college%20thesis%20in%20biomedical%20engineering%2C%20I%20realized%20my%20strengths%20were%20more%20rooted%20in%20the%20medical%20world.%20I%20trained%20in%20emergency%20medicine%20and%20practiced%20for%20about%2010%20years.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EDuring%20that%20time%2C%20NASA%20was%20accepting%20applicants%20from%20outside%20physicians%20for%20flight%20surgeon%20roles%2C%20whose%20jobs%20would%20be%20to%20take%20care%20of%20astronauts.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20NASA%20selection%20process%20varies%20depending%20on%20the%20role%20and%20the%20makeup%20of%20the%20corps.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20my%20view%2C%20they%20look%20for%20people%20with%20technical%20expertise%20in%20something%2C%20a%20wide%20skill%20set%2C%20and%20the%20ability%20to%20communicate%20well%20on%20technical%20and%20non-technical%20topics.%20NASA%20is%20also%20interested%20in%20how%20candidates%20have%20pushed%20themselves%20outside%20of%20work%20and%20the%20calculated%20risks%20they've%20taken.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhen%20I%20applied%20in%201994%2C%20I%20looked%20at%20what%20accepted%20astronauts%20had%20done%2C%20made%20a%20list%20of%20what%20resonated%2C%20and%20started%20checking%20off%20the%20boxes.%20That's%20how%20I%20did%20it%20%E2%80%94%20but%20there's%20not%20one%20way%20to%20become%20an%20astronaut.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%22689%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Portrait%20of%20Tom%20Marshburn%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F687e49043d5881a51c1dacb9%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22860%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3ETom%20Marshburn%20joined%20NASA%20in%201994.%3Cp%3ENASA%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EI%20joined%20NASA%20in%201994.%20During%20that%20time%2C%20I%20spent%20three%20months%20learning%20Russian%20before%20heading%20to%20Star%20City%2C%20the%20cosmonaut%20training%20center%20outside%20Moscow.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThere%20are%20events%20in%20training%2C%20particularly%20in%20Russia%2C%20where%20there%20was%20absolute%20exhaustion%2C%20both%20physical%20and%20mental.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EI've%20never%20been%20as%20hyperthermic%20or%20hypothermic%20as%20I%20was%20in%20Russia%20for%20both%20winter%20survival%20and%20summer%20water%20survival%20training.%20At%20one%20point%2C%20during%20water%20survival%20training%2C%20I%20had%20a%20core%20body%20temperature%20of%20104%C2%B0F.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAnother%20challenge%20was%20being%20away%20from%20my%20family.%20My%20wife%20and%20I%20have%20one%20daughter.%20We%20communicated%20every%20day%20that%20we%20could%2C%20even%20if%20I%20was%20exhausted%2C%20they%20were%20tired%2C%20or%20we%20just%20didn't%20feel%20like%20it.%20We%20did%20it%20anyway%2C%20because%20then%20you%20get%20used%20to%20it%20and%20it%20becomes%20a%20habit.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EI%20spent%20the%20next%20decade%20as%20a%20flight%20surgeon.%20I%20supported%20one%20crew%2C%20then%20various%20crews%2C%20before%20supporting%20NASA's%20entire%20medical%20program%20for%20the%20International%20Space%20Station.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EI%20was%20selected%20to%20become%20an%20astronaut%20in%202004%20and%20spent%2018%20years%20in%20the%20NASA%20Astronaut%20Corps.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%225b788027-f78d-44c4-a422-f096ec5188c5%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EAn%20emergency%20spacewalk%20taught%20me%20about%20preparation%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EMy%20first%20flight%20was%20in%202009%20%E2%80%94%20a%2015-day%20space%20shuttle%20mission%20to%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fastronauts-best-photos-from-space-station-this-year-2024-12%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22%5C%22%3EInternational%20Space%20Station%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20or%20ISS.%20At%20the%20launchpad%2C%20there's%20a%20huge%20sense%20of%20excitement.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAt%20your%20first%20launch%2C%20there's%20some%20trepidation.%20It's%20like%20you're%20about%20to%20take%20the%20biggest%20final%20exam%20of%20your%20life.%20Typically%2C%20you%20don't%20get%20a%20lot%20of%20sleep%2C%20but%20there's%20a%20lot%20of%20laughter%20and%20anticipation.%20On%20that%20mission%2C%20I%20did%20three%20spacewalks.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMy%20second%20flight%20was%20in%20late%202012.%20I%20flew%20to%20the%20ISS%20aboard%20a%20Russian%20Soyuz.%20I%20had%20no%20spacewalks%20planned%2C%20but%20about%20three%20days%20before%20I%20was%20set%20to%20come%20back%2C%20in%20May%202013%2C%20there%20was%20an%20emergency%20%E2%80%94%20a%20leak%20of%20ammonia%20coolant.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIf%20you%20lose%20the%20coolant%2C%20the%20power%20system%20can%20overheat%2C%20and%20then%20you%20have%20to%20shut%20it%20down%2C%20which%20is%20a%20really%20big%20deal.%20Preparing%20for%20a%20spacewalk%20typically%20takes%20nine%20weeks%2C%20and%20we%20had%20a%20matter%20of%20hours.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIt%20taught%20me%20that%20preparation%20matters.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMission%20control%20had%20the%20plan.%20We%20just%20followed%20their%20lead%2C%20step%20by%20step.%20It%20was%20one%20of%20the%20best%20examples%20of%20teamwork%20I've%20ever%20had%20the%20privilege%20of%20being%20a%20part%20of.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAll%20the%20years%20of%20training%20and%20experience%20meant%20we%20were%20prepared%20and%20had%20the%20confidence%20to%20handle%20that%20situation.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%228d83dd2e-9fa5-4c37-bedf-998798c43cad%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3ETransition%20to%20the%20private%20sector%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EFrom%202021%20to%202022%2C%20I%20was%20part%20of%20the%20SpaceX%20Crew-3%20mission%20for%20about%20six%20months.%20It%20was%20my%20final